@NODE New12 "CS1x Editor - What is New in Release 1.2?"

@{b}@{u}CS1x Editor - What is New in Release 1.2?@{uu}@{ub}

Here's a list of the most important changes since release 1.1.

@{fg shine}1. Fixed Arpeggiator Editor@{fg text}
A  bug  was  introduced in version 1.1, which caused inexplicable and weird
behaviour  of the gadgets onscreen during Arpeggiator Editor.  This problem
has been fixed.
@{"  " LINK Arp} Arpeggiator Editor

@{fg shine}2. Added "FC Vari Control Depth" parameter@{fg text}
An  attentive  user  pointed out to me that there was no way to control the
"FC  Vari  Control  Depth".  I was shocked!  The parameter is now available
for editing in the "MW, PB, FC, Porta Editor".
@{"  " LINK Porta} MW, PB, FC, Porta Editor

@{fg shine}3. Added "Chorus To Reverb Send" parameter@{fg text}
To  my  horror  there  was  another  parameter missing:  the Send Chorus To
Reverb parameter!  It can now be edited from the Effects Editor.
@{"  " LINK Effects} Effects Editor

@{fg shine}4. Improved the CS1x System Editor@{fg text}
The  CS1x  System  Editor is now devided in two editors; one for the Master
Parameters  and  the  usual  System  stuff,  and  a  completely new one for
Assigning  controller  numbers  to  CS1x  controls.   You  can  even select
controllers by name now!
@{"  " LINK System} CS1x System Editor

@{fg shine}5. Added Local On/Off to CS1x System Editor@{fg text}
You  can now control the Local ON/OFF function from the CS1x System Editor.
In  previous  version  there  was no way to control this parameter from the
Editor.  Another missing parameter found!
@{"  " LINK System1} Master Parameters / System Editor 1

@{fg shine}6. Improved the Midi THRU function@{fg text}
If  you  turn  ON the MIDI THRU function, the Editor will now automatically
set  the  CS1x  to  Local OFF.  If you turn OFF the MIDI THRU function, the
Editor  will  set  the CS1x to Local ON.  You can monitor this behaviour in
the  CS1x  System  Editor.  If you manually force the Local ON/OFF function
and the MIDI THRU function in an illogical situation (both ON or both OFF),
the Editor will give a warning.

@{fg shine}7. Fixed the Receive *crash* bug!@{fg text}
I'm in heaven now that I found the bug that crashed version 1.0 and version
1.1 one mouseclick after receiving a performance or bulkdump while you were
in one of the Layers editors.  At least, I think I have...

@{fg shine}8. Rewrote GUI Engine@{fg text}
The  GUI-creation  code  was  thoroughly(!)  revised.  It all works better,
faster  and  more  systematic  now.   This also reduced the executable size
considerably.

@{fg shine}9. Added Random Performance Generator@{fg text}
It  would  be  great  to  have a Random Performance Generator, wouldn't it?
Well, here's one with an adjustable Fruitcake Level! You can find it in the
Performance General Editor.
@{"  " LINK PerfGen} Performance General Editor

@{fg shine}10. Added "Copy Edit Perf." to Bank Manager@{fg text}
You  can  now use a new 'Copy Edit Perf.' button in the Bank Manager to add
performances  to the Destination list that are not yet in any bank!  In the
previous  version  it  was not possible to add seperate performances to the
Destination.
@{"  " LINK Manager} Performance Bank Manager

@{fg shine}11. Added Save As B&P Track@{fg text}
You  can now save the current performance as a Bars & Pipes Track using the
new  menu-option.  You can load these files into Bars & Pipes with the Load
Track option from the Tracks menu.
@{"  " LINK SavePerfBP} Save Performance As Bars & Pipes Track

@{fg shine}12. Added Load B&P Track@{fg text}
Not surprisingly, you can now also load Bars & Pipes Tracks into the Editor
as  the  current  performance.  Be sure to read the extra information about
this new feature, because there are some restrictions here.
@{"  " LINK LoadPerfBP} Load Performance As Bars & Pipes Track

@{fg shine}13. Added Performance Knobs Values Editor@{fg text}
A  new  editor was added to the Performance Editor, with which you can edit
the  value of the six knobs.  The values entered here are used as 'default'
values  for  when  the  performance  is activated.  Previously these values
could not be edited from the Editor, except by receiving them from the CS1x
directly.
@{"  " LINK KnobsVal} Performance Knobs Values Editor

@{fg shine}14. New Manual Guide@{fg text}
You're looking at it. So I'm not kidding! :)

@{fg shine}15. Added System Request feature@{fg text}
After  the  Editor  starts,  it  will  now  automatically  read  the system
parameters  from  the  CS1x, in stead of simply assuming the defaults.  The
parameters can also be read from the CS1x using the new 'Request' button in
the CS1x System Editor.  The parameters that are read from the CS1x can all
be Edited from the CS1x System Editor, and they include:

 - Performance Receive Channel
 - Midi Device Number
 - Keyboard Transpose
 - Keyboard Velocity Curve
 - Keyboard Transmit Channel
 - Midi Local (ON/OFF)
 - Controller numbers (set with the ASSIGN CTRL NO function)
   for the MW, FC, FV, Knobs 1 to 6 and the Foot Switch.
 - Scene Controller (MW or FC)
 - Scene Mode (Off, Scene1, Scene2, Controlled)

Note  that  Master  Volume and Master Tuning are NOT system parameters, and
are therefore not received.  It would be very annoying if they were!
@{"  " LINK System} CS1x System Editor

And if you think that's all: no way! Lot's of other small things have been
changed and/or fixed.

@{u}                                                                           @{uu}

Other links:

    @{"  " LINK New11} What Was New In V1.1?

               - Amiga RealTime CS1x Editor by AlcoRhythm -
@ENDNODE

@NODE New11 "CS1x Editor - What was New in Release 1.1?"

@{b}@{u}CS1x Editor - What was New in Release 1.1?@{ub}@{uu}

Here's a list of the most important changes since release 1.0:

@{fg shine}1. Added the Performance Bank Manager!@{fg text}
You  can  use  this  to  easily  create  new  banks  out  of existing ones.
Performances  can  be  copied  around  at  will  from one of three selected
sources to the destination bank!

@{fg shine}2. Added keyboard shortcuts!@{fg text}
You  can now always use the arrowkeys to scroll through lists (use shift to
go faster).  There's additional keyboard shortcuts for the Filter, AEG, PEG
and  FEG editors as well as for the Performance Bank Maganer.  The HELP key
will show keyboard shortcuts for each editor (if there are any).

@{fg shine}3. Real-Time update from selection lists!@{fg text}
The  various  popup  lists now have realtime MIDI-update too!  Selecting an
item in any of these popup lists will immediately provoke a reaction in the
CS1x!

@{fg shine}4. Replaced the Suspend function!@{fg text}
In  the  previous  version,  the  Suspend function would lock up the entire
program  to  free  MIDI  resources.   I've replaced this 'feature' with the
Disable MIDI function, which allows the Editor to run even without MIDI.

@{fg shine}5. Added information in the screentitle@{fg text}
In  the  title  bar  of  the screen, you can now always see the name of the
current  performance.   If  you are in one of the Performance Layer Editors
you  can  also  see the names of the voices in all layers.  The name of the
voice in the current layer is surrounded with '[' and ']'.

@{fg shine}6. Fixed one >crash< bug!@{fg text}
Version 1.0 would crash ..sometimes..  if you tried to use Load Performance
from  the  menu  while you were in one of the Performance Layer Editors.  I
believe I've fixed this problem.

@{fg shine}7. Fixed the Mute function!@{fg text}
There were some rather unpleasant inconsistancies in the way the Mute flags
worked in version 1.0.  The Mute flags now always work, even when you're in
the  Voice  List.

@{fg shine}8. Added list select for Arpeggiator Subdivision!@{fg text}
If  you  thought  the list of options in the cycle gadget for selecting the
Arpeggiator  Subdivision was too long, you now have the option of selecting
the desired value from a popup list.

@{fg shine}9. Changed the Performance Scenes Editor@{fg text}
In  the  previous  version you could only switch the CS1x Scenes on and off
from  the  CS1x  System  editor.   Now  you can control the Scene modes and
controller from the Performance Scenes Editor too.

@{fg shine}10. Made Changes to Performance Layer Effect Editor@{fg text}
An  extra  button  was  added  to the Performance Layer Effects Editor that
allows you to quickly go to the Performance Effects Editor and back.  Also,
I   finally  figured  out  why  layers  Reverb  and  Chorus  aren't  always
independently  controllable  in  the CS1x.  The behaviour of the Editor now
matches that of the CS1x!

@{fg shine}11. New CS1x Prefs Editor@{fg text}
It  is  now possible to edit the preferences file using an external program
called  CS1xEditPrefs.   This  allows you to set the default screenmode and
MIDI  options.   You  can  also  change  the  way  the  Edit Performance is
initialised.

@{fg shine}12. Save as ASCII Text@{fg text}
The  Editor  can now save formatted ASCII Text files of performance or bulk
dumps.   The  generated  file  is  80  columns  wide,  and contains the HEX
formatted sys/ex codes.  Maybe you can find a use for it!

And lot's of other (smaller) changes!

@{u}                                                                           @{uu}

               - Amiga RealTime CS1x Editor by AlcoRhythm -
@ENDNODE


@NODE WhatIs "CS1x Editor - What is The CS1x Editor?"

@{u}@{b}CS1x Editor - What is The CS1x Editor?@{ub}@{uu}

The RealTime CS1x Editor is a set of about 20 different editors that can be
used  to  edit  ALL  parameters  of performances in the YAMAHA CS1x Control
Synthesizer.   All  parameters  are  accessed  through  logically layed out
screens and are real-time updated over MIDI.

Here's some of the most important features of this Editor:

@{fg shine}Features:@{fg text}
 - ALL PARAMETERS ARE UPDATED REALTIME OVER MIDI!
   Dragging a slider, pressing a button or typing a value will cause
   immediate updates to occur in the CS1x for ALL parameters.
 - Easy GUI with all parameters grouped together in logical groups.
 - Graphical editors for cut-off filter, AEG, FEG and PEG.
 - Big buttons and sliders for more precision.
 - Easy selection of voices from a categorised voicelist.
   Each category can be made visible or invisible at any time.
   There are search and sorting options available as well.
 - Random Performance Generator with adjustable Fruitcake Level!
 - Layers can be muted for better pre-view listening.
 - Keyboard shortcuts for common operations.
 - You can select voices from the XG Bank, Material Voice Bank, XG SFX Bank
   AND the Demo Bank 'Drum Machine' for use in performances!
 - Fast send and receive of Bulk Dumps and Performance Dumps.
 - List select for many items.
 - Load and save sys/ex files of Performance or Bulk Dumps.
 - Load and save performances as Bars & Pipes Tracks.
 - Uses the MIDI library.
 - Performance Bank Manager for creating new banks from existing banks.
 - Easily accessable About requester...
 - Work with any device number, configurable from the editor.
 - Work on any screenmode sized 640x200 or bigger.
 - Edit all parameters of the Variation Effect.
 - Also works without MIDI.
 - CS1x-style receive for bulkdump and performance dumps:
   just send it over and CS1x Editor will receive and record.
 - CS1x style edit buffer. Changes will not immediately destroy old data.
 - Automatic reading of CS1x System parameters.
 - MIDI Thru option.
 - Easy to use.
 - Much, much, much more!

@{fg shine}Requirements:@{fg text}
 - An Amiga with WB2.0 or better.
 - A MIDI interface connected to your Amiga.
 - A CS1x synth connected to your MIDI interface.
 - The MIDI.library (included).

@{u}                                                                           @{uu}

Related Topics:

  @{"  " LINK New12}  What's New in Release 1.2?

               - Amiga RealTime CS1x Editor by AlcoRhythm -
@ENDNODE


@NODE Prefs "CS1x Editor - CS1x Editor Prefs"

@{u}@{b}CS1x Editor - CS1x Editor Prefs@{ub}@{uu}

The  Preferences  editor is a separate program named 'CS1xEditorPrefs'.  To
start  it,  simply  doubleclick  it's  icon  from  the workbench.  Use this
program to configure some defaults used by the CS1x Editor.

The following options are available from the preferences window:

@{fg shine}Change Screen@{fg text}
Press this button to bring up a screenmode requester.  By using this method
of  presetting  the screenmode, you will not need to promote the CS1xEditor
screen.  You can also set the screenmode from within the CS1x Editor.

@{fg shine}Startup Defaults@{fg text}
Under this header you find a cycle gadget with which you can change the way
the  CS1x  Editor  will initialise the edit performance.  Note that you can
not  change  this  option  from within the CS1x Editor.  Also note that the
setting  you  choose  here  is used for startup as well as the Re-Init MIDI
option from the Options menu.  You have the following options:

  @{b}Send --:Empty Performance@{ub}
Use  this  if  you  want CS1x Editor to send an --:Empty performance to the
CS1x  after  startup.  This is what the original version of CS1x Editor did
and it is the default setting.

  @{b}Receive Current Performance@{ub}
Use this if you want CS1x Editor to send out a Dump Request for the current
performance  after  startup.   This  means that the editor will receive the
current  edit  performance  from  the CS1x.

@{fg shine}Disable MIDI?@{fg text}
If you check this checkbox, CS1x Editor will disable MIDI at startup.  Note
that  you  can  not  change  this setting from within CS1x Editor.  You can
re-enable  MIDI  from  within the CS1x Editor, but that setting will not be
saved.

@{fg shine}Connect MIDI THRU?@{fg text}
If  you  check  this checkbox, CS1x Editor will automatically create a MIDI
Thru  connection  at  program  startup.   Note that you can not change this
setting  from  within  CS1x Editor.  You can turn MIDI THRU on and off from
within the CS1x Editor, but that setting will not be saved.

@{fg shine}Device No@{fg text}
Choose the device number to use.  The CS1x Editor will assume that the CS1x
is  present  at  this  device number, the next time it is started.  You can
also set this value from within the CS1x Editor.

@{fg shine}Defaults@{fg text}
Press this to reset the preferences to default.

@{fg shine}Use@{fg text}
This will exit the program, saving the changes to the preferences file.

@{fg shine}Cancel@{fg text}
This will exit the program, without saving the changes.



@{fg shine}About The Configuration File@{fg text}
The  configuration  file  is located in the S:  directory, and has the name
'CS1xEdit.config'.   The  CS1x  Editor  will  attempt  to read this file at
startup.   When it fails, the Editor will use defaults.  When you quit CS1x
Editor,  it  will write the configuration file back to disk.  This way, the
CS1x  Editor  can  remember  the Device Number and screenmode settings last
used,  and  use  them  again next time it is started.  CS1x Editor will not
save  all  settings though:  e.g.  the MIDI THRU option is not saved.  This
is  because you will probably only use these options incidentally.  This is
why  there is a separate Prefs program:  these defaults CAN be changed with
the CS1x Prefs Editor.

If  there is no configuration file, one will be created by either the Prefs
program or the CS1x Editor.  Whichever you use first.

These are the defaults used when no prefs file is found:

  Screenmode    : $8000 (High Res)
  Screensize    : 640x256 (8 colours)
  Startup Action: Send --:Empty Performance
  MIDITHRU      : Off
  Disable MIDI  : Off
  Device No.    : All (17)

NOTE:   The configuration file is compatible with the configuration file of
the previous versions.  The exact format of the file is private.

@{u}                                                                           @{uu}

               - Amiga RealTime CS1x Editor by AlcoRhythm -
@ENDNODE


@NODE Startup "CS1x Editor - Starting the Editor"

@{u}@{b}CS1x Editor - Starting the Editor@{ub}@{uu}

Before  starting the Editor, make sure your CS1x is turned ON and connected
to your Amiga in the correct way.

If this is the first time you ever start the CS1x Editor, you might want to
use  the  CS1xEditPrefs  program  first  to pre-set the screenmode and some
other settings.

After  that,  doubleclick  the CS1x Editor icon and wait for it to load up.
After  the  screen  opens,  the  Editor  will  attempt  to  load  the  file
'default.bank'.   While  it is loading, you will see a progress indication.
If  the  file  is  not  available, it is simply not loaded (the file is not
required).

After  loading  is  finished,  the CS1x should be in Performance Mode.  The
Editor  will  now  first  read  the  CS1x  System parameters from the CS1x.
Depending  on  the settings in the CS1xEditPrefs program, one of two things
will now happen:

  1.  A performance called --:Empty will be sent to the CS1x.  You will see
  a short 'Receiving' message in the CS1x display.  After that, the display
  should  read  '--:Empty  ' and the 'E' (edit) sign should be visible.  If
  you play the CS1x, you don't hear any sound.  This is correct.

or

  2.  The CS1x Editor will send a dump request to the CS1x, after which you
  will  see  the 'Receiving' window on the CS1x Editor screen.  After that,
  the  edit performance in the CS1x Editor should have the same name as the
  current  performance  of  the  CS1x.   If you play the CS1x, you hear the
  current performance.  This is correct.

At  this  point  the  Editor  is  ready for use, except when something went
wrong.  In that case, read the Trouble Shooting section.

To get started with the Editor, read the section about general operation.

@{u}                                                                           @{uu}

Related Topics

  @{"  " LINK Trouble}  Trouble Shooting
  @{"  " LINK Prefs}  CS1x Edit Prefs
  @{"  " LINK General}  General Operation

               - Amiga RealTime CS1x Editor by AlcoRhythm -
@ENDNODE


@NODE General "CS1x Editor - General Operation"

@{u}@{b}CS1x Editor - General Operation@{ub}@{uu}

This section describes how to use the Editor in general.

Throughout  the  program,  the  CS1x  Editor  will always display a list of
buttons  on  the  left.   These buttons can be used to navigate through the
various editors on the right.  Each editor will give you access to a number
of CS1x parameters.  Related parameters are grouped together in one editor.

The  space  for the list of buttons will be called the Buttons List Window.
The  space  for the editors on the right will be called the Editors Window.

After  startup,  the  first  Editor  you  will  see is the Performance List
Editor.  Here you can select a performance to edit.  Each time you select a
performance  from  the  list,  it  is  sent  to the CS1x so you can test it
immediately.   To edit the performance, press the button 'Edit Performance'
in  the  Buttons  List  Window  or  press  the 'Edit' button in the Editors
Window.

This will bring up the Performance Editor General.  The Buttons List Window
displays  a  new  set of buttons.  At the bottom-left of the screen you can
find  the  'Back'  button,  which can take you back to the previous editor.
You  will  find this button in all editors, except ofcourse the Performance
List Editor (which has no previous Editor).

After  you  finished  editing  the  performance,  you  can  go  back to the
Performance  List  Editor.  You will see the edited performance in the list
has  '(E)'  appended to it's name to indicate that it has changed.  At this
point, all the changes are still not permanent.

In the Performance List Editor there is a 'Store' button where you normally
find the 'Back' button.  Press this to store the current performance in the
current  bank  permanently.   If  you neglect to store the performance, you
will  loose the performance the next time you select a performance from the
list!   The idea behind this is that it somewhat resembles the way the CS1x
works:   if you edit the current performance on the CS1x and then press the
PROGRAM  +/-  buttons, the edited performance is lost unless you STORE'd it
first.

If  you  want  to store the current performance in another performance than
the  currently  selected,  you have to press the 'Copy' button, then select
the performance where you wish to store the new performance, and then press
'Paste'.

For  more information about how to use the various editors, see the section
about The Editors.

@{u}                                                                           @{uu}

Related Topics:

  @{"  " LINK Editors}  The Editors

               - Amiga RealTime CS1x Editor by AlcoRhythm -
@ENDNODE


@NODE Editors "CS1x Editor - Using the Editors"

@{u}@{b}CS1x Editor - Using the Editors@{ub}@{uu}

This section describes how to use all the functions of the CS1x Editor.
The space for the list of buttons will be called the Buttons List Window.
The space for the editors on the right will be called the Editors Window.


@{b}Buttons List Window:@{ub}

  @{"  Load Performance  " LINK LoadPerf} - Load a performance
  @{"  Save Performance  " LINK SavePerf} - Save current performance
  @{"  Send Performance  " LINK SendPerf} - Resend current performance
  @{"  Load Bank         " LINK LoadBank} - Load a performance bank
  @{"  Save Bank         " LINK SaveBank} - Save current performance bank
  @{"  Send Bank         " LINK SendBank} - Send current performance bank
  @{"  Request Perf      " LINK Request} - Request current performance

  @{"  Perf. Manager     " LINK Manager} - Performance Bank Manager
  @{"  CS1x System       " LINK System} - CS1x System Editor

  @{"  Edit Performance  " LINK EditPerf} - @{fg shine}Performance Editor@{fg text}

  @{"  Store             " LINK Store} - Store current performance


@{b}Editors Window:@{ub}

  @{" Performance List   " LINK PerfList} - Performance List Editor

@{u}                                                                           @{uu}

               - Amiga RealTime CS1x Editor by AlcoRhythm -
@ENDNODE

@NODE LoadPerf "CS1x Editor - Load Performance"

@{u}@{b}CS1x Editor - Load Performance@{ub}@{uu}

Loads  a  'single  performance' dump file.  You can create these files with
any  sys/ex  receiving  program,  or with the CS1x Editor itself.  The file
contains seven sys/ex messages containing all the performance data.

The  file  is  loaded  into  the editor as the 'Current Performance'.  That
means   that  it  replaces  all  changes  you  have  made  to  the  current
performance.  The newly loaded file will not be stored in the current bank,
until you press the 'Store' button.

The  CS1x  Editor  behaves  the  same as the CS1x when it receives a single
performance  dump:  if you don't store the new performance, it will be lost
when you change program.

@{u}                                                                           @{uu}

Related Topics:

  @{"  " LINK LoadPerfBP}  Load Bars & Pipes Track
  @{"  " LINK LoadBank}  Load Performance Bank

               - Amiga RealTime CS1x Editor by AlcoRhythm -
@ENDNODE

@NODE LoadPerfBP "CS1x Editor - Load B&P Track"

@{u}@{b}CS1x Editor - Load B&P Track@{ub}@{uu}

Loads  a  'single  performance'  from  a  Bars & Pipes Track file.  You can
create  these  files  with Bars & Pipes Pro 2.5 or with the CS1x Editor
itself.

The Performance Dump must be on a track with no other data than sys/ex data
(so  no  notes,  controllers,  program  changes etc.) preceeding the actual
dump.   There  may be extra sys/ex codes before the dump starts, these will
be ignored. If other data is found, you will get an error message.

The  file  is  loaded  into  the editor as the 'Current Performance'.  That
means   that  it  replaces  all  changes  you  have  made  to  the  current
performance.  The newly loaded file will not be stored in the current bank,
until you press the 'Store' button.

The  CS1x  Editor  behaves  the  same as the CS1x when it receives a single
performance  dump:  if you don't store the new performance, it will be lost
when you change program.

@{u}                                                                           @{uu}

Related Topics:

  @{"  " LINK LoadPerf}  Load Performance
  @{"  " LINK LoadBank}  Load Performance Bank

               - Amiga RealTime CS1x Editor by AlcoRhythm -
@ENDNODE

@NODE LoadBank "CS1x Editor - Load Bank"

@{u}@{b}CS1x Editor - Load Bank@{ub}@{uu}

Loads  a  complete  CS1x  Bulk  dump  file.   This  will  replace  all  the
performances  in the current bank.  The current performance buffer will not
change, so if you were editing a performance, it is not lost when loading a
new  bank.   You  will  ofcourse loose all other performances.  This is the
same behaviour as the CS1x when it receives a complete bulk dump.

@{u}                                                                           @{uu}

Related Topics:

  @{"  " LINK LoadPerf}  Load Performance
  @{"  " LINK LoadPerfBP}  Load Bars & Pipes Track

               - Amiga RealTime CS1x Editor by AlcoRhythm -
@ENDNODE

@NODE SavePerf "CS1x Editor - Save Performance"

@{u}@{b}CS1x Editor - Save Performance@{ub}@{uu}

Saves  the  current  performance  to a 'single performance' dump file.  The
file  will  contain  seven sys/ex messages containing all performance data.
Note that all non-stored changes are also saved to the file.  The resulting
file contains exactly the same information as a 'Bulk Dump 1 Perf' from the
CS1x.

You  can  load  these files back into the Editor with 'Load Performance'.

@{u}                                                                           @{uu}

Related Topics:

  @{"  " LINK SavePerfBP}  Save Performance As Bars & Pipes Track
  @{"  " LINK SavePerfASCII}  Save Performance As ASCII Text
  @{"  " LINK SaveBank}  Save Performance Bank
  @{"  " LINK SaveBankASCII}  Save Performance Bank As ASCII Text

               - Amiga RealTime CS1x Editor by AlcoRhythm -
@ENDNODE

@NODE SavePerfBP "CS1x Editor - Save Bars & Pipes Track"

@{u}@{b}CS1x Editor - Save Bars & Pipes Track@{ub}@{uu}

Saves the current performance to Bars & Pipes Track file. This file can be
loaded into Bars & Pipes Professional using the 'Load Track' option in the
'Tracks' menu.

Assuming a 4/4 beat, the following data will be on the track:

  0001:01:000  ; nothing
  0001:02:000  ; sys/ex block 1
  0001:03:000  ; sys/ex block 2
  0001:04:000  ; sys/ex block 3
  0002:01:000  ; sys/ex layer 1
  0002:02:000  ; sys/ex layer 2
  0002:03:000  ; sys/ex layer 3
  0002:04:000  ; sys/ex layer 4

Note that all non-stored changes are also saved to the file.  The resulting
file contains exactly the same information as a 'Bulk Dump 1 Perf' from the
CS1x.

You  can  load  these files back into the Editor with 'Load B&P Track'.

@{u}                                                                           @{uu}

Related Topics:

  @{"  " LINK SavePerf}  Save Performance
  @{"  " LINK SavePerfASCII}  Save Performance As ASCII Text
  @{"  " LINK SaveBank}  Save Performance Bank
  @{"  " LINK SaveBankASCII}  Save Performance Bank As ASCII Text

               - Amiga RealTime CS1x Editor by AlcoRhythm -
@ENDNODE

@NODE SavePerfASCII "CS1x Editor - Save Performance As ASCII Text"

@{u}@{b}CS1x Editor - Save Performance As ASCII Text@{ub}@{uu}

Saves the current performance to an ASCII Text File.  The file will contain
all  seven  sys/ex  messages  containing  all  performance  data, formatted
80-columns wide in HEX format.

Note that all non-stored changes are also saved to the file.  The resulting
file contains exactly the same information as a 'Bulk Dump 1 Perf' from the
CS1x.

You can not load these files back into the Editor.

@{u}                                                                           @{uu}

Related Topics:

  @{"  " LINK SavePerf}  Save Performance
  @{"  " LINK SavePerfBP}  Save Performance As Bars & Pipes Track
  @{"  " LINK SaveBank}  Save Performance Bank
  @{"  " LINK SaveBankASCII}  Save Performance Bank As ASCII Text

               - Amiga RealTime CS1x Editor by AlcoRhythm -
@ENDNODE

@NODE SaveBank "CS1x Editor - Save Performance Bank"

@{u}@{b}CS1x Editor - Save Performance Bank@{ub}@{uu}

Saves  all  128  performances  in  the current bank to a Bulk Dump All Perf
file.   The file will contain the sys/ex codes for every performance in the
bank.  If the current performance was not stored before you saved the bank,
the changes made to that performance are not recorded in the file.

The file can be loaded back into the Editor with 'Load Bank'.

@{u}                                                                           @{uu}

Related Topics:

  @{"  " LINK SavePerf}  Save Performance
  @{"  " LINK SavePerfBP}  Save Bars & Pipes Track
  @{"  " LINK SavePerfASCII}  Save Performance As ASCII Text
  @{"  " LINK SaveBankASCII}  Save Performance Bank As ASCII Text

               - Amiga RealTime CS1x Editor by AlcoRhythm -
@ENDNODE

@NODE SaveBankASCII "CS1x Editor - Save Performance Bank As ASCII Text"

@{u}@{b}CS1x Editor - Save Performance Bank As ASCII Text@{ub}@{uu}

Saves  all 128 performances in the current bank to an ASCII Text file.  The
file  will  contain  the  sys/ex  codes  for every performance in the bank,
formatted  in  80-columns  wide HEX format.  If the current performance was
not  stored before you saved the bank, the changes made to that performance
are not recorded in the file.

The file can not be loaded back into the Editor.

@{u}                                                                           @{uu}

Related Topics:

  @{"  " LINK SavePerf}  Save Performance
  @{"  " LINK SavePerfBP}  Save Bars & Pipes Track
  @{"  " LINK SavePerfASCII}  Save Performance As ASCII Text
  @{"  " LINK SaveBank}  Save Performance Bank

               - Amiga RealTime CS1x Editor by AlcoRhythm -
@ENDNODE


@NODE SendPerf "CS1x Editor - Send Performance"

@{u}@{b}CS1x Editor - Send Performance@{ub}@{uu}

Use this to manually send the current performance to the CS1x.

CS1x  Editor  will  keep the CS1x up to date of any changes you make to the
current  performance,  so in general you will not need to send performances
manually.

@{u}                                                                           @{uu}

Related Topics:

  @{"  " LINK SendBank}  Sending a Performance Bank

               - Amiga RealTime CS1x Editor by AlcoRhythm -
@ENDNODE

@NODE SendBank "CS1x Editor - Send Bank"

@{u}@{b}CS1x Editor - Send Bank@{ub}@{uu}

This  will send all performances in the bank to the CS1x.  The performances
will  overwrite  all  performances that are already in the user-bank of the
CS1x.

Note  that  if  the current performance was not stored, any changes made to
that performance are not send to the CS1x.

@{u}                                                                           @{uu}

Related Topics:

  @{"  " LINK SendPerf}  Sending a Performance

               - Amiga RealTime CS1x Editor by AlcoRhythm -
@ENDNODE

@NODE Request "CS1x Editor - Performance Request"

@{u}@{b}CS1x Editor - Performance Request@{ub}@{uu}

When  you  select  'Request  Performance',  the CS1x will send it's current
performance  to  the  Editor.   You  will see the 'Receiving' window pop up
while  seven blocks of data are received.  Before requesting a performance,
first  select  the  performance  you  want to receive using the PROGRAM +/-
buttons on the CS1x panel.

The  dump  is  recorded in the current performance buffer, which means that
you have to store it if you want to keep it.

NOTE:   You  may  also start the performance dump manually using the Dump 1
Perf option in UTILITY mode of the CS1x.

@{i}Remarks@{ui}
Why  is  there no 'Request Bank' function?  I can almost hear you ask.  The
reason  is  that  requesting  an  entire bank from the CS1x is really slow.
Instead,  you have to start a 'Bulk Dump All' manually from the CS1x.  It's
almost twice as fast.

@{u}                                                                           @{uu}

               - Amiga RealTime CS1x Editor by AlcoRhythm -
@ENDNODE

@NODE Manager "CS1x Editor - The Performance Bank Manager"

@{u}@{b}CS1x Editor - The Performance Bank Manager@{ub}@{uu}

The  Performance  Bank  Manager  can be used to compose new banks using the
performances of existing banks.  You can load up to two reference banks and
use  them together with the current edit bank to create a new bank.  On the
screen  you  see  two lists.  The list on the left contains the source bank
(the  bank from which to copy performances), the list on the right displays
the destination bank (the new bank to copy to).

If  you  select  a  performance  in  the sourcelist, you can copy it to the
destination  list  by pressing the 'Copy (To Destination)' button.  You can
copy no more than 128 performances into the destination, ofcourse!

If  you  select a performance from the destination list, you can move it up
and  down  the list, or remove it from the list with the associated buttons
beneath the destination list.

A  selected  performance  (from  either  list)  will  be  sent  to the CS1x
immediately,  so  you can test the performance directly.  When you're happy
with the destination list, press 'Use New Bank' to use the destination bank
as the current bank, or press 'Back' to cancel the changes.


@{b}Buttons List Window:@{ub}

@{fg shine}Load Ref. Bank 1@{fg text}
Loads   a   bulk  dump  file  in  reference  bank  1.   The  sourcelist  is
automatically set to Ref.  Bank 1 after loading.

@{fg shine}Load Ref. Bank 2@{fg text}
Load a bulk dump file in reference bank 2.  The sourcelist is automatically
set to Ref.  Bank 2 after loading

@{fg shine}Empty Ref. Bank 1@{fg text}
Clear all performances from reference bank 1.

@{fg shine}Empty Ref. Bank 2@{fg texT}
Clear all performances from reference bank 2.

@{fg shine}Copy All@{fg text}
Copies  all performances from the sourcelist to the destination list.  Note
that all performances that were already in the destination will be lost.

@{fg shine}Copy Edit Perf.@{fg text}
Takes  the  performance  from  the  current  Edit Buffer and adds it to the
destination  list.  This way it is possible to add single performances that
are  not  in  any  bank yet to the destination bank.  To add another single
performance to the Destination, simply load one using 'Load'->'Performance'
or  'Load  B&P  Track'->'Performance'  from the Project menu, and press the
'Copy Edit Perf.' button again.

@{fg shine}Use New Bank@{fg text}
This  will  close  the  Performance  Bank  Manager and take you back to the
Performance  List  Editor.  The bank in the destination list is used as the
new  performance  bank.   If  there  are  less than 128 performances in the
destination  list,  the  rest  of  the  bank  will  be  filled  with  empty
performances.   Note that all performances that were in the 'old bank' will
be lost.

@{fg shine}Back@{fg text}
This  will also close the Performance Bank Manager and take you back to the
Performance List Editor.  The destination list is not used as the new bank,
and  the  old bank will remain intact.  The bank will be the same as it was
before  you  entered the Bank Manager (except if you loaded a new one while
you were in the manager!).


@{b}Editor Window:@{ub}

@{fg shine}Source:@{fg text} (cycle gadget)
Select which source bank you want to use. You have the following options:
 - Old Bank    = The bank that was currently loaded in the editor.
 - Ref. Bank 1 = The bank that was loaded as reference bank 1.
 - Ref. Bank 2 = The bank that was loaded as reference bank 2.

@{fg shine}Find:@{fg text} (string gadget)
Enter a string to find in the names of the performances in the source list.
Only  performances that contain this string in their name will be listed in
the  source list.  If you enter no string, all performances in the selected
source bank are listed in the source list.

@{fg shine}Copy (To Destination)@{fg text}
Copy the currently selected source performance to the destination list.  If
no  source  is  selected, nothing happens.  The new item is inserted before
the item that was last selected in the destination list.  If no destination
item  was  selected  before, the new performance is added at the end of the
list.

@{fg shine}Move Up@{fg text}
Moves  the  currently  selected  destination  performance  one  up  in  the
destination list.  If no destination is selected, nothing happens.

@{fg shine}Move Down@{fg text}
Moves  the  currently  selected  destination  performance  one  down in the
destination list.  If no destination is selected, nothing happens.

@{fg shine}Remove@{fg text}
Deletes the currently selected destination performance from the destination
list.  If no destination is selected, nothing happens.

@{fg shine}Clear List@{fg text}
Deletes all performances from the destination list.

@{b}TIP:@{ub}
Press  the  HELP  key while you are in the Performance Bank Manager to get
information about keyboard shortcuts!

@{u}                                                                           @{uu}

               - Amiga RealTime CS1x Editor by AlcoRhythm -
@ENDNODE

@NODE System "CS1x Editor - CS1x System Editor"

@{u}@{b}CS1x Editor - CS1x System Editor@{ub}@{uu}

Use   this  editor  to  change  CS1x  Master  Parameters  and  CS1x  System
Parameters.  Note that some of these parameters are pretty low level, so be
careful!   Also  be  aware that none of these parameters can be stored in a
performance.   The  System Editor is devided in two parts, accessed through
the buttons in the Button List Window.


@{b}Buttons List Window:@{ub}

  @{"  Master / System 1  " LINK System1} - Master Parameters / System Editor 1
  @{"  System 2           " LINK System2} - System Editor 2 (Assignable Controllers)

  @{"  Request            " LINK ReqSys} - Request Current System


@{b}Editors Window:@{ub}
Here you can see the selected System Editor.
See Button List Window for more information.

@{u}                                                                           @{uu}

               - Amiga RealTime CS1x Editor by AlcoRhythm -
@ENDNODE

@NODE System1 "CS1x Editor - Master Parameters / System Editor 1"

@{b}CS1x Master Parameters:@{ub}

@{fg shine}Master Volume:@{fg text}
The CS1x Master Volume level.  The effect is the same as using the 'VOLUME'
knob on the CS1x.  Note that changing the Master Volume affects all of your
CS1x...  if you forget to turn up the volume again, your CS1x may go silent
on you semi-permanently!

@{fg shine}Master Tune:@{fg text}
For  editing  the  Master  Tuning  of  the CS1x.  This is the same value as
'MASTER TUNE' in Utility mode of your CS1x.


@{b}CS1x System Parameters:@{ub}

@{fg shine}Device Number:@{fg text}
Use  this  to  set  the Device Number used by the CS1x and the CS1x Editor.
Always make sure that the CS1x and the CS1x Editor both use the same device
number!   In  the  Editor a value of '17' corresponds to 'All' in the CS1x.
To  check  the  device  number  settings,  put the CS1x in Utility mode and
select 'DEVICE NO'.  Then drag the slider around a bit and see if the value
on  the  display  of the CS1x matches the value on screen.  Once the device
numbers match, you will see that the CS1x display keeps track of the slider
when you move it!  The default value is 'All'.
@{"  " LINK Trouble} Trouble Shooting

@{fg shine}Velocity Curve:@{fg text}
Choose the type of velocity curve you wish to use.

@{fg shine}Fix Velocity:@{fg text}
If  zero,  this  value  has  no  effect.   Otherwise it will set the 'Fixed
Velocity'  value.  This means that keyboard velocity has no effect, and all
notes will sound at the same level of velocity.

@{fg shine}Transpose:@{fg text}
Set the keyboard transpose level.

@{fg shine}Transmit Channel:@{fg text}
Set the transmit channel for the performance mode.

@{fg shine}Perf. Rcv. Channel:@{fg text}
Set the receive channel for the performance mode.

@{fg shine}Scene Controller:@{fg text}
Select which controller you wish to use to control the scene modes.

@{fg shine}Scene Mode:@{fg text}
Here  you  can  put  the  scene mode in 'Off', 'Scene1', 'Scene2' or 'Scene
Control'.   In  'Scene  Control'  mode  you  can  use  the  selected  Scene
Controller to do transitions between the two scenes.

@{u}                                                                           @{uu}

Related Topics:

  @{"  " LINK System2}  System Editor 2 (Assignable Controllers)
  @{"  " LINK SysReq}  Request Current System

               - Amiga RealTime CS1x Editor by AlcoRhythm -
@ENDNODE


@NODE System2 "CS1x Editor - System Editor 2 (Assignable Controllers)"

@{u}@{b}CS1x Editor - System Editor 2 (Assignable Controllers)@{ub}@{uu}

@{i}In  the  CS1x, this feature is called 'ASSIGN CTRL NO.' and you can find it
in UTILITY mode.  It's easier from the Editor.@{ui}

Here  you  can  choose  the controller numbers that the CS1x should use for
it's  controls (knobs, wheels and pedals).  For each control you can select
a  controller  number  between  0  and  95.   The  CS1x  uses some of these
controllers  to  control  it's  parameters.  For example, controller number
seven is used to control volume levels.  So if you select controller number
seven  for the Mod Wheel, from then on the Mod Wheel can be used to control
volume level.  Also the Mod Wheel will now cause controller number seven to
be sent out via MIDI.

The CS1x utilises the following (named) controllers:

   1  Mod Depth
   5  Porta Time
   6  Data MSB
   7  Main Volume
  10  Pan Pot
  11  Expression ( = Volume)
  16  General 1
  17  General 2
  18  General 3
  19  General 4
  38  Data LSB
  64  Hold 1
  65  Porta Switch
  66  Sostenuto
  67  Soft
  71  Harmonic Contents ( = Resonance)
  72  Release Time
  73  Attack Time
  74  Brightness ( = Cutoff)
  84  Porta Control
  91  Reverb Send
  93  Chorus Send
  94  Variation Send

The  other controllers have no effect on the CS1x, but it can send them out
via  MIDI.   You  can use these 'unnamed controllers' to control other MIDI
devices from the CS1x.

To  set  a  controller  number for a CS1x control, simply drag the relevant
slider  or  enter  the  number  in the integer gadget.  You can also select
'List' to bring up the above list of named controllers.  From this list you
can  easily (and only) select controllers that are used by (and have a name
in) the CS1x.

The defaults (factory set) values are as follows:

  MW          =  1  Mod Depth
  FC          = 16  General 1
  FV          = 17  General 2
  Knob 1      = 73  Attack Time         (ATTACK knob)
  Knob 2      = 72  Release Time        (RELEASE knob)
  Knob 3      = 17  General 2           (ASSIGN 1/DATA knob)
  Knob 4      = 74  Brightness          (CUTOFF knob)
  Knob 5      = 71  Harmonic Contents   (RESONANCE knob)
  Knob 6      = 18  General 3           (ASSIGN 2 knob)
  Foot Switch = 64  Hold 1

You can instantly call up these defaults if you press 'Reset Controllers'.

@{u}                                                                           @{uu}

Related Topics:

  @{"  " LINK System1}  Master Parameters / System Editor 1
  @{"  " LINK SysReq}  Request Current System

               - Amiga RealTime CS1x Editor by AlcoRhythm -
@ENDNODE


@NODE SysReq "CS1x Editor - Request Current System"

@{u}@{b}CS1x Editor - Request Current System@{ub}@{uu}

If  you  press this button, the Editor will attempt to read the CS1x System
parameters  from  the  CS1x.   After you press the button, you will see the
gadgets  for  the involved parameters update.  The following parameters are
read from the CS1x:

  - Performance Receive Channel
  - Midi Device Number
  - Keyboard Transpose
  - Keyboard Velocity Curve
  - Keyboard Transmit Channel
  - Midi Local (ON/OFF)
  - Controller numbers (set with the ASSIGN CTRL NO function)
    for the MW, FC, FV, Knobs 1 to 6 and the Foot Switch.
  - Scene Controller (MW or FC)
  - Scene Mode (Off, Scene1, Scene2, Controlled)

Note  that  Master  Volume and Master Tuning are NOT system parameters, and
are therefore not received.

Normally  you should not need to use the 'Request' button, because the CS1x
Editor  will automatically read the CS1x System parameters at the following
occasions:

  - Just after program startup
  - When you turn off the 'Disable MIDI' feature
  - When you use the 'Re-Init MIDI' feature

@{u}                                                                           @{uu}

Related Topics:

  @{"  " LINK System1}  Master Parameters / System Editor 2
  @{"  " LINK System2}  System Editor 2 (Assignable Controllers)

               - Amiga RealTime CS1x Editor by AlcoRhythm -
@ENDNODE

@NODE EditPerf "CS1x Editor - The Performance Editor"

@{u}@{b}CS1x Editor - The Performance Editor@{ub}@{uu}

From  here  you can edit all Performance Common parameters of the CS1x.  To
edit  Performance  Layer  parameters,  select  the 'Layers' button from the
Buttons  List.   All  parameters are updated realtime over MIDI, so you can
immediately hear the effect of any change you make.

@{b}Buttons List Window:@{ub}

  @{"  Performance        " LINK PerfGen} - Performance General Editor
  @{"  Effects            " LINK Effects} - Performance Effects Editor
  @{"  Scenes             " LINK Scenes} - Performance Scenes Editor
  @{"  Knobs Values       " LINK KnobsVal} - Performance Knobs Values Editor
  @{"  Knobs Assign       " LINK Knobs} - Performance Knobs Assign Editor
  @{"  Arpeggiator        " LINK Arp} - Performance Arpeggiator Editor
  @{"  MW, PB, FC, Porta  " LINK Porta} - Performance MW/PB/FC/Porta Editor

  @{"  Layers             " LINK Layers} - @{fg shine}Performance Layer Editors@{fg text}


@{b}Editors Window:@{ub}
Shows the selected editor.
See Buttons List Window for more details about the Editors.

@{u}                                                                           @{uu}

               - Amiga RealTime CS1x Editor by AlcoRhythm -
@ENDNODE

@NODE PerfGen "CS1x Editor - Performance General Editor"

@{u}@{b}CS1x Editor - Performance General Editor@{ub}@{uu}

In this small editor screen you can edit the Performance category, name and
common  volume.   Change  the category using the cycle gadget, or press the
List button to select a category from a list. Ofcourse both parameters are
updated immediately in the CS1x.


@{fg shine}Random Performance Generator@{fg text}
Use  this  to, well...  generate random performances!  Adjust the Fruitcake
Level  to  suit  your  needs.   In  general,  a higher Fruitcake Level will
generate  weirder  performances.   The new performance is sent to the CS1x,
and   will  overwrite  any  changes  you  may  have  made  to  the  current
performance,  so  watch  what  you're  doing!  Great toy when you're out of
inspiration!

@{u}                                                                           @{uu}

               - Amiga RealTime CS1x Editor by AlcoRhythm -
@ENDNODE

@NODE VoiceList "CS1x Editor - Voice List"

@{u}@{b}CS1x Editor - Voice List@{ub}@{uu}

The  Voice  List  is  much like the Performance List Editor.  You have some
more  options  available  though,  because  the  Voice List is a BIG thing!
Select  the  voice  you  want to use from the Voice List by clicking on it.
You  can  de-select  a  voice  by  clicking  on it again.  If you press the
'Accept'  or 'Okay' button, the currently selected voice is accepted as new
voice  for  the layer, if you press 'Back', the selected voice is not used.
Press 'Accept' with no voice selected to turn the layer off.  If you select
a  voice,  you  can instantly hear it in the current layer!  Use the 'Mute'
flags in the menu if you want to hear it more clearly! You can also see the
name of the selected voice in the display of the CS1x(!).

@{fg shine}Category Flags:@{fg text}
With the checkboxes on the right you can turn on and off certain categories
of voices in the voice list.  This will reduce the length of the list which
is pretty handy when you are looking for a specific kind of sound.

@{fg shine}List:@{fg text} (cyclegadget)
With  the  cycle gadget 'List:' you can choose what banks you want to list.
You  can  set  it  to  'All Voices', 'Material', 'XG', 'SFX' or even 'Dance
Machine'  (the  undocumented  Demo Bank of the CS1x).  The list may be VERY
long  if  you  set this gadget to 'All Voices', but you can reduce it using
the available filtering options.  Note the voices in the Dance Machine Demo
Bank  have no registered name in the CS1x, and that you can not access this
bank  in  any  way  from  the  CS1x control panel(s).  Also note that these
voices will not be in the list when the list is set to 'All Voices'!

@{fg shine}Find:@{fg text}
In  this  stringgadget  you  can  enter a string to find in the performance
names.   If you type nothing (empty string), all voices are listed.  If you
enter  a  string,  then only those voices that contain that string in their
name  will  be  listed.   So  if  you  enter  'oo'  then  only  voices like
'VoiceOoh',  'Bassoon',  'Woodblock'  etc.   will  be  in the list.  In the
resulting list you can still filter the categories using the checkboxes.

@{fg shine}Sort By Number@{fg text}
The  voicelist  is  presented  in  order  of appearance, sorted by bank and
program numbers.

@{fg shine}Sort By Name@{fg text}
The voicelist is presented in alphabetical order of voicenames.

@{fg shine}Sort By Category@{fg text}
The  voicelist  is  presented  in  order  of  category.  All categories are
grouped together.  The order within each category is meaningless.

@{fg shine}Okay@{fg text}
Press  this  to  accept the currently selected voice.  You can also use the
'Accept'  button  to  do  this.   Use the 'Back' button to cancel the Voice
List.

@{u}                                                                           @{uu}

               - Amiga RealTime CS1x Editor by AlcoRhythm -
@ENDNODE

@NODE Effects "CS1x Editor - Performance Effects Editor"

@{u}@{b}CS1x Editor - Performance Effects Editors@{ub}@{uu}

In  this  editor  you  can  choose  the  effects  you  wish to use for your
performance.

@{fg shine}Reverb Type:@{fg text}
Select a Reverb effect type to use.

@{fg shine}Chorus Type:@{fg text}
Select a Chorus effect type to use.

@{fg shine}Chorus -> Reverb:@{fg text}
Control the amount of Chorus effect you want to send to Reverb.

@{fg shine}Vari Type:@{fg text}
Select a Variation Effect type to use.

For  the  Vari Effect Type you can also edit the parameters for the effect.
Use  the sliders to change the values.  For each Variation Effect there are
different  parameters  to  edit.  All changes you make are sent to the CS1x
immediately, so you can hear everything change in realtime.

@{u}                                                                           @{uu}

               - Amiga RealTime CS1x Editor by AlcoRhythm -
@ENDNODE

@NODE Scenes "CS1x Editor - Performance Scenes Editor"

@{u}@{b}CS1x Editor - Performance Scenes Editor@{ub}@{uu}

Here  you  can edit the two scene modes of the CS1x.  Using the sliders you
can  set the knob values for all six knobs in both scenes.  You can use the
two cyclegadgets at the top to change the scene modes.

@{fg shine}Left cyclegadget:@{fg text}
 - Scenes Off          = No scene modes
 - Scene 1 On          = Enable scene 1 (top LED = on)
 - Scene 2 On          = Enable scene 2 (bottom LED = on)
 - Scene Controller On = Control the scenes with the Scene Controller
                         (both LEDs are on)

@{fg shine}Right cyclegadget:@{fg text}
 - ModWheel Control    = Use ModWheel as Scene Controller.
 - Foot Control        = Use Foot Controller as Scene Controller.


NOTE: These two values can also be controlled from the @{"CS1x System Editor" LINK System}.
Neither values can be stored in the Performance.

@{u}                                                                           @{uu}

               - Amiga RealTime CS1x Editor by AlcoRhythm -
@ENDNODE

@NODE KnobsVal "CS1x Editor - Performance Knobs Values Editor"

@{u}@{b}CS1x Editor - Performance Knobs Values Editor@{ub}@{uu}

Here  you  can  edit  the 'current' value of the six knobs.  The values you
enter  here  will  be  used as the 'default' values when the performance is
selected.   So  every  time you select the performance from the Performance
List  Editor,  or  from  the  CS1x  control  panel,  the  six knobs will be
initialised to these values.

@{u}@{b}TIP:@{ub}@{uu}
You  can  also  set  the  knobs directly on the CS1x panel, and then select
'Request Performance' (RightAmiga+R) to transfer the new knob values to the
Editor.

@{u}                                                                           @{uu}

               - Amiga RealTime CS1x Editor by AlcoRhythm -
@ENDNODE

@NODE Knobs "CS1x Editor - Performance Knobs Assign Editor"

@{u}@{b}CS1x Editor - Performance Knobs Assign Editor@{ub}@{uu}

Use  this  editor  to  set  the parameters for knob 6 (ASSIGN 2) and knob 3
(ASSIGN 1/DATA).

@{fg shine}Knob 3:@{fg text}
Select  a  parameter  using  the  Cyclegadget or press 'List' to bring up a
selection list.

@{fg shine}Knob 6:@{fg text}
Use  the  cyclegadgets  to  browse  through the available options, or press
'List'  to  select a parameter from a list.  With the 'Layer x' gadgets you
can  select  for  which  layer  the  parameter  should  be  used.  With the
'Sensitivity'  sliders  you  can  change the amount of effect the parameter
will have.

All changes are sent to the CS1x immediately, so you can test everything in
realtime!

@{u}                                                                           @{uu}

               - Amiga RealTime CS1x Editor by AlcoRhythm -
@ENDNODE

@NODE Arp "CS1x Editor - Performance Arpeggiator Editor"

@{u}@{b}CS1x Editor - Performance Arpeggiator Editor@{ub}@{uu}

Here  you  can  set  the  various  options  for the arpeggiator.

@{fg shine}Arpeggiator:@{fg text}
Use this cycle gadget to put the arpeggiator in one of three modes:
  - Off   (no arpeggiator)
  - On    (arpeggiator plays while keys are down)
  - Hold  (arpeggiator plays continuously after first key-down)

@{fg shine}Type:@{fg text}
Select  an  arpeggiator type using the 'Type' cycle gadget, or press 'List'
to bring up a selection list.

@{fg shine}Subdivision:@{fg text}
Select  the  subdivision  of  a  note  to use for the arpeggiator, or press
'List' to bring up a selection list.

@{fg shine}Tempo:@{fg text}
Set the tempo in BPM for the Arpeggiator.

@{fg shine}MIDI Tempo:@{fg text}
Activate  the  'MIDI Tempo' to enable synchronisation of the Arpeggiator to
an external MIDI clock. The 'Tempo' setting is then ignored.

@{fg shine}Split:@{fg text}
Turn  the  arpeggiator split on and off.  If on, only the lower two octaves
of the keyboard will trigger the Arpeggiator.

@{u}                                                                           @{uu}

               - Amiga RealTime CS1x Editor by AlcoRhythm -
@ENDNODE

@NODE Porta "CS1x Editor - Performance MW, PB, FC, Porta Editor"

@{u}@{b}CS1x Editor - Performance MW, PB, FC, Porta Editor@{ub}@{uu}

@{fg shine}MW = Mod Wheel@{fg text}
Edit  the  amount  of  effect  you want the Mod Wheel to have on any of the
following parameters:
 - Filter Control               - open/close the cutoff filter with MW
 - LFO Pitch Modulation Depth   - control the vibrato effect for pitch
 - LFO Filter Modulation Depth  - control the vibrato effect for filter

@{fg shine}PB = Pitch Bend@{fg text}
Edit the range of the pitch bend wheel in number of semitones.

@{fg shine}FC = Foot Controller@{fg text}
Edit  the  amount  of effect you want the Foot Controller to have on any of
the following parameters:
 - Filter Control               - control the cutoff filter
 - LFO Filter Modulation Depth  - control the 'vibrato' effect for filter
 - Vari Control Depth           - control the variation effect

@{fg shine}Porta = Portamento@{fg text}
Control the Portamento Time and Portamento Switch.

@{u}                                                                           @{uu}

               - Amiga RealTime CS1x Editor by AlcoRhythm -
@ENDNODE

@NODE Layers "CS1x Editor - Performance Layers Editors"

@{u}@{b}CS1x Editor - Performance Layers Editors@{ub}@{uu}

From  here  you  can edit all the Performance Layer parameters of the CS1x.
To  edit  the Performance Common parameters again, press the Back button at
the bottom of the Buttons List Window.

@{b}Buttons List Window:@{ub}

  @{"  Layer x             " LINK LayerAct} - Activate Layer x
  @{"  Copy                " LINK LayerCopy} - Copy All Current Layer Parameters
  @{"  Paste               " LINK LayerPaste} - Paste All Current Layer Parameters

  @{"  General             " LINK GenLayer} - Performance Layer General Editor
  @{"  Velocity            " LINK Velo} - Performance Layer Velocity Editor
  @{"  Effects             " LINK LayerFX} - Performance Layer Effects Editor
  @{"  LFO                 " LINK LFO} - Performance Layer LFO Editor
  @{"  Filter              " LINK Filter} - Performance Layer Filter Editor
  @{"  Amplitude Envelope  " LINK AEG} - Performance Layer AEG Editor
  @{"  Pitch Envelope      " LINK PEG} - Performance Layer PEG Editor
  @{"  Filter Envelope     " LINK FEG} - Performance Layer FEG Editor


@{b}Editors Window:@{ub}
This shows the selected Layers Editor.
See the Buttons List Window for more information.

@{u}                                                                           @{uu}

               - Amiga RealTime CS1x Editor by AlcoRhythm -
@ENDNODE

@NODE LayerAct "CS1x Editor - Activate Layer"

@{u}@{b}CS1x Editor - Activate Layer@{ub}@{uu}

Press  one  of  the  four layer selection buttons to activate a layer.  The
active  editor  in  the  Editors  Window  will  update to reflect the newly
selected layer.

@{u}                                                                           @{uu}

               - Amiga RealTime CS1x Editor by AlcoRhythm -
@ENDNODE

@NODE LayerCopy "CS1x Editor - Copy Layer"

@{u}@{b}CS1x Editor - Copy Layer@{ub}@{uu}

This  will  copy  all  parameters  in  the  current layer to the Layer Copy
Buffer.   Use  the 'Paste' button to transfer the parameters from the Layer
Copy Buffer to a layer again

@{u}                                                                           @{uu}

Related Topics:

  @{"  " LINK LayerPaste}  Paste Layer

               - Amiga RealTime CS1x Editor by AlcoRhythm -
@ENDNODE

@NODE LayerPaste "CS1x Editor - Paste Layer"

@{u}@{b}CS1x Editor - Paste Layer@{ub}@{uu}

Use  this  to  transfer the current Layer Copy Buffer to the current layer.
If  there  is no data in the buffer, nothing will happen.  To put data into
the Layer Copy Buffer you can use the 'Copy' button.

@{u}                                                                           @{uu}

Related Topics:

  @{"  " LINK LayerCopy}  Copy Layer

               - Amiga RealTime CS1x Editor by AlcoRhythm -
@ENDNODE

@NODE GenLayer "CS1x Editor - Performance Layer General Editor"

@{u}@{b}CS1x Editor - Performance Layer General Editor@{ub}@{uu}

@{fg shine}Voice:@{fg text}
Select a voice to use for this layer using the @{"Voice List" LINK VoiceList}.
You can see "Category: Name  MSB/LSB/Program  [(Mute)]" here.

@{fg shine}Volume:@{fg text}
Set the volume level for this layer.

@{fg shine}Panning Mode:@{fg text}
 - Normal Panning : Use the panning level set with the 'Panning:' slider.
 - Random Panning : Put each note at a random position in the stereo space.

@{fg shine}Panning:@{fg text}
Control the panning level:
   0 = Center
 -63 = Left
 +63 = Right

@{fg shine}Play Mode:@{fg text}
 - Polyphonic : support multiple sounds to play at once.
 - Monophonic : only one sound can play at any time.

@{fg shine}Note Shift:@{fg text}
Transpose the layer with a number of semitones.

@{fg shine}Note Limit:@{fg text}
 - Low  : Note number beneath which this layer is to produce no sound.
 - High : Note number above which this layer is to produce no sound.

@{fg shine}Detune:@{fg text}
Detune the layer from the other layers.

@{u}                                                                           @{uu}

               - Amiga RealTime CS1x Editor by AlcoRhythm -
@ENDNODE

@NODE Velo "CS1x Editor - Performance Layer Velocity Editor"

@{u}@{b}CS1x Editor - Performance Layer Velocity Editor@{ub}@{uu}

Here  you  can  edit  several  parameters  regarding  the keyboard velocity
settings.

@{fg shine}Sensitivity:@{fg text}
 - Level   : How sensitive this layer is to velocity.
 - Offset  : Value to add to the velocity.

@{fg shine}Limit@{fg text}
 - Low     : Velocity beneath which this layer is to produce no sound.
 - High    : Velocity above which this layer is to produce no sound.

@{u}                                                                           @{uu}

               - Amiga RealTime CS1x Editor by AlcoRhythm -
@ENDNODE

@NODE LayerFX "CS1x Editor - Performance Layer Effects Editor"

@{u}@{b}CS1x Editor - Performance Layer Effects Editor@{ub}@{uu}

Here you can edit effects at layer level.

@{fg shine}Reverb Send@{fg text}
Controls the amount of Reverb effect for this layer.

@{fg shine}Chorus Send@{fg text}
Controls the amount of Chorus effect for this layer.

@{fg shine}Enable Variation Effect@{fg text}
If checked, the Variation Effect is enabled for this layer.

@{fg shine}Effects Editor@{fg text}
Press this button to quickly go to the Effects Editor.

@{fg shine}Vari On -> Reverb Send@{fg text}
Here  you  can see the amount of Reverb effect that is used for layers that
have the Variation Effect enabled.

@{fg shine}Vari On -> Chorus Send@{fg text}
Here  you  can see the amount of Chorus effect that is used for layers that
have the Variation Effect enabled.


@{fg shine}Note on 'Vari On -> xxxxx Send' Parameters@{fg text}
When  the CS1x uses the Variation Effect, the result of that effect must go
to  Chorus and Reverb.  The Variation Effect works for all layers that have
the  effect  enabled,  and  will result in a single signal that goes to the
Chorus  and  Reverb  effects.   This means that the different layers are no
longer   seperated   (the  Variation  effect  has  effectively  mixed  them
together).   Therefore  you  can  no  longer  control the Reverb and Chorus
levels of these layers independently.

@{i}Example:@{ui}
Let's say you enable Variation Effect for layer 1 and 2.  If you now change
the   Reverb  level  for  layer  1,  the  Reverb  level  at  layer  2  will
automatically  change to the same value.  This common value is displayed in
the 'Vari On -> Reverb Send' display.  On the other hand, if you change the
Reverb  for  layer  3,  no  other  layers  will change with it, because the
Variation Effect was not enabled for layer three.  Layers 3 and 4 are still
independently controllable.

@{u}                                                                           @{uu}

Related Topics:

  @{"  " LINK Effects}  Performance Effects Editor

               - Amiga RealTime CS1x Editor by AlcoRhythm -
@ENDNODE

@NODE LFO "CS1x Editor - Performance Layer LFO Editor"

@{u}@{b}CS1x Editor - Performance Layer LFO Editor@{ub}@{uu}

This is where you can change the LFO (Low Frequency Oscillator) settings of
the current layer.

@{fg shine}Key Sync:@{fg text}
How to respond to key presses.
 --           = Normal.
FreeRun       = Free running oscillator, no response to keypresses.
Retrigger     = Restart oscillator after each keypress.

@{fg shine}Wave:@{fg text}
What type of waveform to use for the oscillation.
--            = Normal Sine wave.
Saw           = Sawtooth wave.
Tri           = Trianglular wave.
Sample & Hold = Random-like wave.

@{fg shine}Speed:@{fg text}
How fast the oscillator should run.

@{fg shine}AMod Depth:@{fg text}
Amplitude Modulation Depth. How much you want the amplitude to change.

@{fg shine}PMod Depth:@{fg text}
Pitch Modulation Depth. How much you want the pitch to change (vibrato).

@{fg shine}FMod Depth:@{fg text}
Filter Modulation Depth. How much you want the filter to change.

@{u}                                                                           @{uu}

               - Amiga RealTime CS1x Editor by AlcoRhythm -
@ENDNODE

@NODE Filter "CS1x Editor - Performance Layer Filter Editor"

@{u}@{b}CS1x Editor - Performance Layer Filter Editor@{ub}@{uu}

Here  you  can  edit  the cutoff filter and resonance level for the current
layer.

Use  the  sliders  to change the cutoff and resonance levels.  You will see
that  the graphical representation also changes.  You can also grab hold of
the graphic and drag it around with the mouse!  Or use the arrowkeys on the
keyboard to control the filter.  Ofcourse everything is sent to the CS1x as
it  happens,  so  you  can  hear the effect instantly.  This is fun to play
with...  remember to keep breathing!

@{fg shine}NOTE:@{fg text}
The  parameters  'Cutoff'  and  'Resonance'  of  the  Filter  Editor can be
influenced by the CUTOFF and RESONANCE knobs on the CS1x.  If you enter the
Filter  Editor,  you are advised to put these knobs in the neutral position
(centered).   In  the  Filter  editor  you  are  always editing the neutral
position of the knobs.  The CS1x adds the values of the knobs to the values
you set with the Filter Editor!

@{u}                                                                           @{uu}

               - Amiga RealTime CS1x Editor by AlcoRhythm -
@ENDNODE

@NODE "AEG" "CS1x Editor - Performance Layer AEG Editor"

@{b}@{u}CS1x Editor - Performance Layer AEG Editor@{uu}@{ub}

Here  you  can  edit  the  Amplitude  Envelope  Generator parameters of the
current layer.

Use the sliders to change the various parameters.  Watch the graphic change
to see what you are doing.  You can also drag the editpoints in the graphic
and watch the sliders change.  Or use the arrowkeys on the keyboard to move
the  current  editpoint  (use  TAB to select another point).

@{fg shine}NOTE:@{fg text}
The  parameters  'Attack  Time' and 'Release Time' of the AEG Editor can be
influenced  by  the ATTACK and RELEASE knobs on the CS1x.  If you enter the
AEG  Editor,  you  are  advised  to put these knobs in the neutral position
(centered).   In the AEG editor you are always editing the neutral position
of  the knobs.  The CS1x adds the values of the knobs to the values you set
with the AEG Editor!

@{u}                                                                           @{uu}

Related Topics:

  @{"  " LINK PEG}  Performance Layer PEG Editor
  @{"  " LINK FEG}  Performance Layer FEG Editor

               - Amiga RealTime CS1x Editor by AlcoRhythm -
@ENDNODE


@NODE "PEG" "CS1x Editor - Performance Layer PEG Editor"

@{b}@{u}CS1x Editor - Performance Layer PEG Editor@{uu}@{ub}

Here  you  can  edit the Pitch Envelope Generator parameters of the current
layer.

Use the sliders to change the various parameters.  Watch the graphic change
to see what you are doing.  You can also drag the editpoints in the graphic
and watch the sliders change.  Or use the arrowkeys on the keyboard to move
the  current  editpoint (use TAB to select another editpoint).

@{u}                                                                           @{uu}

Related Topics:

  @{"  " LINK AEG}  Performance Layer AEG Editor
  @{"  " LINK FEG}  Performance Layer FEG Editor

               - Amiga RealTime CS1x Editor by AlcoRhythm -
@ENDNODE


@NODE "FEG" "CS1x Editor - Performance Layer FEG Editor"

@{b}@{u}CS1x Editor - Performance Layer FEG Editor@{uu}@{ub}

Here  you  can edit the Filter Envelope Generator parameters of the current
layer.

Use the sliders to change the various parameters.  Watch the graphic change
to see what you are doing.  You can also drag the editpoints in the graphic
and watch the sliders change.  Or use the arrowkeys on the keyboard to move
the  current  editpoint  (use TAB to select another editpoint).

TIP:   In  some  occasions it's better to turn up the resonance level a bit
when  editing  the  FEG.   This  way you can hear more clearly what you are
doing.

@{u}                                                                           @{uu}

Related Topics:

  @{"  " LINK AEG}  Performance Layer AEG Editor
  @{"  " LINK PEG}  Performance Layer PEG Editor

               - Amiga RealTime CS1x Editor by AlcoRhythm -
@ENDNODE

@NODE Store "CS1x Editor - Store"

@{u}@{b}CS1x Editor - Store@{ub}@{uu}

When  you  have  finished  editing  a  performance, use 'Store' to fix your
changes.  After storing, all changes are recorded in the performance bank.

If  you  are  unhappy with your changes, simply don't store the performance
and  select  another  performance  to edit.  Note that if you re-select the
edited performance from the list, all of the changes are also deleted.

Storing a performance has no effect on the current performance or the CS1x.
It only affects the Performance Bank in the CS1x Editor.  Remember to store
performances  before  you use Send Bank or Save Bank, otherwise the changes
are not sent/saved.

@{u}                                                                           @{uu}

               - Amiga RealTime CS1x Editor by AlcoRhythm -
@ENDNODE

@NODE PerfList "CS1x Editor - Performance List Editor"

@{u}@{b}CS1x Editor - Performance List Editor@{ub}@{uu}

This is the first editor you see when you start the CS1x Editor.

In  the  Performance List Editor you can select the performance you wish to
edit.   To  select  a performance, simply click on it with the mouse.  When
you  look  over  at  you  CS1x's  display,  you  will  see the 'Receiving!'
indication.   Each  time you select a performance, it is sent to the CS1x's
current  performance  buffer,  so  you  can  immediately  test and hear the
selected  performance.   You  can  also  use  the  arrow  keys  to select a
performance.

The  @{b}checkboxes@{ub} on the far right of the screen allow you to turn on and off
individual  categories.  This way you can reduce the length of the list for
better  overview.   The  category checkboxes have no effect on performances
which don't have a category (--)!  These performances will always be in the
list.  The same goes for the currently selected performance.

Use  the  @{b}Copy@{ub} and @{b}Paste@{ub} buttons to copy performances around the list.  You
can also @{b}Swap@{ub} performances or @{b}Move@{ub} them @{b}Up@{ub} and @{b}Down@{ub} the list.

If  you  press  @{b}Edit@{ub}  you  can begin to edit the selected performance.  All
changes you make are recorded in an internal Edit Buffer, so no changes are
made  to  the  selected  performance directly.  When you go back (using the
'Back'  button  at  the  bottom left of the screen) to the Performance List
Editor  you  will  see  the  '(E)' indication after the current performance
name,  just  like  the  'E'  you  see on the CS1x's display when you change
something  there.   This  means that the performance was edited but not yet
stored.  When you are happy with the edited performance, simply press @{b}Store@{ub}
to  fix  the changes and make them permanent.  To cancel the changes simply
select  another  performance  to  edit, or the same performance over again.

@{u}                                                                           @{uu}

Related Topics:

  @{"  " LINK Store}  Store
  @{"  " LINK EditPerf}  Edit Performance

               - Amiga RealTime CS1x Editor by AlcoRhythm -
@ENDNODE


@NODE Author "CS1x Editor - Using The Author"

@{u}@{b}CS1x Editor - The Author@{ub}@{uu}

I  am  AlcoRhythm  of  The  Problem  (an  Amiga based music group) from The
Netherlands  (party!).  Some may know me from earlier days when I was still
active  in the MODs scene for Amiga.  Nowadays I still do mods on occasion,
but I have moved on to the CS1x and Bars & Pipes Professional (wow!  what a
cool program that is!).

I've  created  various CS1x songs, which are available as MIDI files on the
CS1x  sites  such as the official CS1x Archive and the unofficial CS1x/AN1x
Archive.   Ofcourse  the songs were done with Bars & Pipes, and my RealTime
CS1x Editor.  Some of my songs:

    Planning 98                             - Drum N Bass
    Princessa                               - Club Trance
    Who'se Afraid Of Beeps, Beats and Blue? - Goa
    Iridescence                             - Hard/Epic Trance
    Post Immortal Paradox Anomaly           - Hard Trance

Further  more  I released a sample editor with full MIDI support for Sample
Dump  Standard  called  ProDUMP  and  a  small database program for quickly
finding  CS1x  Material  voices  called 'CS1xFind' (doh!).  There were more
programming releases, but not in the field of MIDI.

Working  on  the  songs,  I  often  needed  a  CS1x  Editor.  So I took the
challenge  and created one!  With help from Infinity (another member of The
Problem),  I  input  thousands  of  lines of data such as the CS1x Material
Voice  list,  XG Voice list and the CS1x Effect Parameter list.  Then I put
them all together in this CS1x Editor!

Guilty as charged for creating a full featured CS1x Editor (again) is:

Alco Lammers   (alias AlcoRhythm of The Problem)
Lage Veld 114
7122 ZK AALTEN
The Netherlands
+31 (0)543 475746

E-Mail:
alcorhythm@hotmail.com

For a quick response, E-Mail is the preferred method of communication.

@{u}                                                                           @{uu}

               - Amiga RealTime CS1x Editor by AlcoRhythm -
@ENDNODE

