@NODE NewPerf "CS1x Editor - New Performance"

@{u}@{b}CS1x Editor - New Performance@{ub}@{uu}

This  will  create  a  new  --:Empty  performance  in the Edit buffer.  All
changes  you  had  made  to  the  current  performance  will  be lost.  The
performances in the bank are not affected, only the edit buffer is.

@{u}                                                                           @{uu}

Related Topics:

@{"  " LINK NewBank}  New Bank

               - Amiga RealTime CS1x Editor by AlcoRhythm -
@ENDNODE

@NODE NewBank "CS1x Editor - New Bank"

@{u}@{b}CS1x Editor - New Bank@{ub}@{uu}

This  will  create  an  entire bank filled with --:Empty performances.  All
performances  that were in the current bank will be lost.  The current Edit
performance  is  not affected, only the 128 performances stored in the bank
are.

@{u}                                                                           @{uu}

Related Topics:

@{"  " LINK NewPerf}  New Performance

               - Amiga RealTime CS1x Editor by AlcoRhythm -
@ENDNODE

@NODE About "CS1x Editor - About"

@{u}@{b}CS1x Editor - About@{ub}@{uu}

Brings  up  the  About  requester which displays information about the CS1x
Editor.   It  also  brings  you  up  to  date on the current device number,
current edit performance and the availability of MIDI resources.

@{u}                                                                           @{uu}

               - Amiga RealTime CS1x Editor by AlcoRhythm -
@ENDNODE

@NODE Quit "CS1x Editor - Quit"

@{u}@{b}CS1x Editor - Quit@{ub}@{uu}

Saves  the  current  device number and screenmode to the configuration file
and  then  exits  the CS1x Editor.  Warning:  you can only use this feature
once per session!

@{u}                                                                           @{uu}

               - Amiga RealTime CS1x Editor by AlcoRhythm -
@ENDNODE

@NODE Screenmode "CS1x Editor - Screenmode"

@{u}@{b}CS1x Editor - Screenmode@{ub}@{uu}

Brings  up  a  screenmode  requester  from  which  you  can  select  a  new
screenmode.   Always  pick  a screenmode that is high-res enough to display
640x200  pixels  at  least  (otherwise you'll get an autoscrolling screen).
The best screenmodes for the Editor should be the around the size 640x400.

When  you  quit  the  CS1x  Editor,  the  screenmode  will  be saved to the
configuration file, so that the same mode can be used next time.

You should not (need to) promote the CS1x Editor screen.

@{u}                                                                           @{uu}

               - Amiga RealTime CS1x Editor by AlcoRhythm -
@ENDNODE

@NODE Disable "CS1x Editor - Disable MIDI"

@{u}@{b}CS1x Editor - Disable MIDI@{ub}@{uu}

This will free all MIDI resources allocated by the CS1x Editor, allowing
other programs to take them. This is necessary if you want to run CS1x
Editor in parallel with e.g. Bars & Pipes Pro.

When  you  re-enable  MIDI,  the  CS1x  Editor  will  go  through  the same
initialisation  procedure as when the program was started to bring the CS1x
up to date with all the changes.

NOTE:   You  do not need to Disable MIDI when you want to run programs that
use  the  midi.library  (like  CS1x  Editor does).  All programs using this
library for MIDI transception can work together, sharing the MIDI port.

@{u}                                                                           @{uu}

               - Amiga RealTime CS1x Editor by AlcoRhythm -
@ENDNODE

@NODE ReInit "CS1x Editor - Re-Init MIDI"

@{u}@{b}CS1x Editor - Re-Init MIDI@{ub}@{uu}

This  will  repeat  the MIDI initialisation procedure that is executed when
the  CS1x Editor is started.  This includes putting the CS1x in performance
mode and sending the current performance to the CS1x (or requesting it from
the CS1x, depending on the preferences settings).

@{u}                                                                           @{uu}

               - Amiga RealTime CS1x Editor by AlcoRhythm -
@ENDNODE

@NODE Thru "CS1x Editor - MIDI Thru"

@{u}@{b}CS1x Editor - MIDI Thru@{ub}@{uu}

This will make sure that all MIDI data (except sys/ex) that is received by
the Editor will be sent back to the CS1x. If you enable this feature, the
CS1x Editor will automatically set the CS1x to MIDI Local Off. Vice versa,
if you disable the MIDI Thru function, the CS1x Editor will set the CS1x to
Local On. You can monitor this behaviour in the CS1x System Editor.

NOTE:
The  Local On/Off function of the CS1x should always be set oposit the MIDI
Thru  function.   If  you  manually  force  the editor into using a 'wrong'
combination  (you  can  do this from the CS1x System Editor) you will get a
warning, telling you what the effect will be of your setting.

@{u}                                                                           @{uu}

               - Amiga RealTime CS1x Editor by AlcoRhythm -
@ENDNODE

@NODE Mute "CS1x Editor - Mute Layer"

@{u}@{b}CS1x Editor - Mute Layer@{ub}@{uu}

Use  the Mute flags to indivually mute layers.  This can be pretty handy if
you  want  to  edit  the layers.  Just turn off the layers that you are not
editing and you can clearly hear what you're doing.  Note that muted layers
are  not  really off, so if you save the performance, the muted layers will
be saved normally.

TIP:
If you ever feel that you are not hearing what you should be hearing, check
if there aren't any mute flags set!

@{u}                                                                           @{uu}

               - Amiga RealTime CS1x Editor by AlcoRhythm -
@ENDNODE




@NODE Trouble "CS1x Editor - Trouble Shooting"

@{u}@{b}CS1x Editor - Trouble Shooting@{ub}@{uu}

Here  are  some  suggestions  on what to do when the editor doesn't startup
normally.

First:

   - Check MIDI connections.
   - Select 'Re-Init MIDI' from the menu (or press RightAmiga + I).

If  the  CS1x  display  gives  you the message 'Device No Error', press the
'PERFORMANCE'  button  on  the  CS1x  to  clear the error.  Now you need to
change the Device Number setting.  Here are two ways of doing that:

   - Press 'UTILITY' to put the CS1x in Utility mode.
   - Select 'DEVICE NO' and note the device number in the CS1x display.
   - In the CS1x Editor on your Amiga press the 'CS1x System' button.
   - Fill in the correct value for 'Device Number:' so that it matches the
     value in the CS1x display.
   - Press the 'PERFORMANCE' botton on the CS1x again to leave the Utility
     mode.

Or, if you want to do it all from the editor:

   - Press the 'CS1x System' button in the Editor.
   - Grab the 'Device Number' slider with the mouse and drag it slowly
     all the way from the left to the right, so that all values are touched
     at least once. (While you drag the slider, the CS1x will automatically
     be found on one of the device numbers. You can see this happen if you
     put CS1x in Utility mode and select 'DEVICE NO').
   - Now drag the slider to the desired Device Number you want to use
     (or type it into the integer-gadget next to the slider).

And, after you've finished going through one of the above lists:

   - In the Editor, press the 'Back' buton at the bottom left of the screen.
   - Select 'Re-Init MIDI' from the options menu (RightAmiga + I).

If you can't get the CS1x Editor to work, please @{"let me know" LINK Author}!

@{u}                                                                           @{uu}

               - Amiga RealTime CS1x Editor by AlcoRhythm -
@ENDNODE


@NODE Tips "CS1x Editor - Tips and Tricks"

@{u}@{b}CS1x Editor - Tips and Tricks@{ub}@{uu}

@{fg shine}TIP: Keyboard shortcuts@{fg text}
Press  the HELP key to bring up a requester with information about keyboard
shortcuts.   Each  editor  has  its  own set of shortcuts.  If no requester
appears, there are no shortcuts.  For example, the arrow keys can always be
used  to scroll through lists.  If used together with shift, you can scroll
faster.  In the Filter, AEG, FEG and PEG editors you can use the arrow keys
to  move  the edit-point (move faster with shift) and the TAB key to select
the  next  edit-point.   Also,  use  the function keys F1, F2, F3 and F4 to
select  the  active  layer  when  you  are  in one of the Performance Layer
Editors!

@{fg shine}TIP: Screenmode@{fg text}
If  you  happen  to  own  a  Multi  Sync  monitor,  try  using  the Euro 72
Productivity  screenmode.   It  suits the Editor perfectly.  Any other high
resolution  screen  sized  640  x 400 will also do nicely.  The editor will
work  fine  with  screens  sized 640 x 200 and bigger.  Bigger screens look
better though.

@{fg shine}TIP: Filter Envelope@{fg text}
When  editing the FEG (Filter Envelope), increase the resonance level a bit
to make changes more audible.

@{fg shine}TIP: Request Performance@{fg text}
If  you  feel  more  confortable  editing  some  parameters from the CS1x's
control  panel (e.g.  switching the Arpeggiator or Scene modes on and off),
feel  free to do so.  After you have made the change(s), use 'Request Perf'
to bring your changes over to the Editor.

@{fg shine}TIP: CS1xEditPrefs@{fg text}
It  is not recommended to use screenmode promotion utilities to promote the
CS1x  Editor  screen.  You can change the screenmode using the 'Screenmode'
menu  option  inside  the  editor.   If  you  want to change the screenmode
without  starting  the CS1x Editor (e.g.  before the first time you start),
you can use the @{"CS1xEditPrefs" LINK Prefs} program to (pre)set the screenmode.

@{fg shine}TIP: Default Bank@{fg text}
When  you  start the CS1x Editor it will attempt to load a bank file called
'default.bank'  from  the  directory from which the editor is started.  You
are free to replace this bank with another bank.  To do this, simply copy a
new  file  over  it,  or save a bank over it from the Editor.  You can even
delete  it,  if  you  don't want to wait for it to load every time.  If the
file  is  not  present,  the editor will startup (faster) with a completely
empty bank.

@{fg shine}TIP: Ultimate Proof@{fg text}
You  can  see  the  CS1x-update  happen in real time.  If you are editing a
parameter  in  the  CS1x Editor, bring the parameter up on the CS1x display
using  it's control panel.  Then edit the parameter from the Editor and you
will see the update happen in real time. Ultimate proof!

@{fg shine}TIP: Silent Random Performances@{fg text}
If you use the Random Performance Generator, and the result is silence, you
can  try  to turn up the Cutoff and Resonance or turn down the Attack.  The
generator never generates silence on purpose, since it always uses at least
one layer, but sometimes it happens that the sound is surpressed by all the
parameters.   And  also  don't  forget  to  check  out  the  scenes after a
performance is generated!

@{u}                                                                           @{uu}

               - Amiga RealTime CS1x Editor by AlcoRhythm -
@ENDNODE


@NODE RealTime "CS1x Editor - What Do You Mean, Real Time?"

@{u}@{b}CS1x Editor - What Do You Mean, Real Time?@{ub}@{uu}

Every  change  you make in the editor will be sent to the CS1x immediately.
This  happens  in  the form of a (stream of) Sys/Ex message(s).  The Editor
ONLY  uses  Sys/Ex  data.

If  you type a number in an integer gadget for example, the value you typed
is sent to the CS1x immedately after you are finished typing.  If you use a
slider,  a  whole  stream  of Sys/Ex data is sent to the CS1x while you are
dragging.   This  offers you a realtime control over every single parameter
in  the CS1x.  You don't even have that kind of control in the CS1x itself!
For instance, you can change every parameter of the Variation Effect, while
you  (or  the  Arpeggiator)  play  notes.   You can hear the effect of each
parameter change in real time.

To  see  this take place with your own eyes, simply bring up a parameter on
the  display  of  the  CS1x  using it's control panel and then use the CS1x
Editor  to  change  that  parameter.   You  will  see that the value in the
display of the CS1x changes while you are using the Editor.

This  real  time  update  goes  for  all  parameters  that  the  Editor can
influence.   This  includes master and system parameters like Master Volume
and  Master  Tune.

Once  you get used to real-time update, you will never want to live without
it again!

@{u}                                                                           @{uu}

               - Amiga RealTime CS1x Editor by AlcoRhythm -
@ENDNODE


@NODE Future "CS1x Editor - Future Plans"

@{u}@{b}CS1x Editor - Future Plans@{ub}@{uu}

I  have  some  things planned for a possible (likely) future version of the
CS1x Editor (random order):

 - Support for reading and writing MIDI files.
 - Part Editors and Drum Setup Editor for the 12 MultiParts.
 - An XG Editor and Drum Setup Editor for Multi Mode (16 parts).
 - Database function with which you can look up the sys/ex and controller
   codes for every single parameter in the CS1x.
 - MIDI input support for some editing functions.
 - AREXX support for Bars & Pipes Pro and OctaMED SoundStudio.
 - Running CS1x Editor in window(s) on the Workbench.
 - Better Random Performance Generator algorithm, with more options.
 - Make it $20 ShareWare?

 - !!! YOUR SUGGESTIONS AND IDEAS GO HERE !!!

If  you  like  these  ideas, or if you have suggestions of your own, please
tell  me!   Any  response  will motivate me to continue development of this
program.

I  have  already  received suggestions and remarks from all over the world,
some  of  which  have resulted in new features (like the Random Performance
Generator).  Others are now in the Future Plans list, so there will be more
to come!  Thanks to all who have sent in their reactions so far, and keep'm
coming!

